Poisson Depth Recovery¶

In the previous work, we introduced the Poisson image editing for seamless editing of images regions. We are now ready to put this knowledge into Poisson depth recovery.

Accessing and Reading Data Sets¶

Note that the depth map and normal map are both generated from mathematical expression, so they can be regarded as ground truth.

Later we will choose some pixels in depth map and the whole normal map to construct the Poisson equation.

In [86]:
mask = np.load("data/mask.npy")
depth = np.load("data/depth.npy")
gt_depth = depth.copy()
normal = np.load("data/normal.npy")

Solve Poisson Equation¶

Load random array to decide which depth map pixels are known. Change the percentage of known depth map pixels.
Use column sparse matrix to build the Poisson equation, save a lot of time.

Apply the weight $w$ to depth map to decide how much we trust our depth map.

  • $w>1$, we trust normal more than depth.
  • $w<1$, we trust depth more than normal.
In [160]:
npy_f_lst = ["data/random_001.npy","data/random_005.npy","data/random_010.npy"]
output_depth = []
for npy_f in npy_f_lst:
    equation_num = 0
    t = np.where(mask==1)
    n = len(t[0])
    k = np.load(npy_f)
    tt = np.array([t[0],t[1]]).T #tt is the known depth pixel's coordinate [[28,128], [29,114]...]
    A_row = []
    A_col = []
    A_data = []
    b = []
    w = 0.1 # the weight for how much we trust the depth map
    d = {} # mapping coordinates with linear indices
    for i in range(n):
        d[(tt[i][0],tt[i][1])] = i
    for i in range(n):
        x = tt[i][0]
        y = tt[i][1]
        if i in k: # if the i-th pixel's depth is known
            A_row.append(equation_num)
            A_col.append(i)
            A_data.append(w)
            b.append(w*depth[x][y])
            equation_num += 1
        else:
            if (x, y-1) in d and (x, y+1) in d and (x-1, y) in d and (x+1, y) in d:
#                 if not(i in k and i-1 in k and i+1 in k and d[(x-1, y)] in k and d[(x+1, y)] in k):
                A_row.append(equation_num)
                A_col.append(i)
                A_data.append(4)
                b.append((normal[x+1][y][1]-normal[x-1][y][1]+normal[x][y+1][0]-normal[x][y-1][0])/2)
                if i-1 in k:
                    b[-1] += depth[x][y-1]
                else:
                    A_row.append(equation_num)
                    A_col.append(i-1)
                    A_data.append(-1)
                if i+1 in k:
                    b[-1] += depth[x][y+1]
                else:
                    A_row.append(equation_num)
                    A_col.append(i+1)
                    A_data.append(-1)

                if d[(x-1, y)] in k:
                    b[-1] += depth[x-1][y]
                else:
                    A_row.append(equation_num)
                    A_col.append(d[(x-1, y)])
                    A_data.append(-1)
                if d[(x+1, y)] in k:
                    b[-1] += depth[x+1][y]
                else:
                    A_row.append(equation_num)
                    A_col.append(d[(x+1, y)])
                    A_data.append(-1)
                equation_num += 1

    A_row = np.array(A_row)
    A_col = np.array(A_col)
    A_data = np.array(A_data)
    b = np.array(b)
    A = sparse.csr_matrix((A_data, (A_row, A_col)), shape=(equation_num, n))
    res = lsmr(A, b)[0]
    for i in range(n):
        x = tt[i][0]
        y = tt[i][1]
        if (x-1, y) in d and (x+1, y) in d and (x, y-1) in d and (x, y+1) in d:
#             if not(i in k and i-1 in k and i+1 in k and d[(x-1, y)] in k and d[(x+1, y)] in k):
            depth[x][y] = res[i]
    output_depth.append(depth)
    depth = gt_depth.copy()

Seperately Use X and Y Component(Non-Poisson Way)¶

We can also seperately use the x-component and y-component of the normal vector.The matrix will be nearly twice taller than Poisson method.

In [144]:
npy_f_lst = ["data/random_001.npy","data/random_005.npy","data/random_010.npy"]
output_depth = []
for npy_f in npy_f_lst:
    equation_num = 0
    t = np.where(mask==1)
    n = len(t[0])
    k = np.load(npy_f)
    tt = np.array([t[0],t[1]]).T #tt is the known depth pixel's coordinate [[28,128], [29,114]...]
    A_row = []
    A_col = []
    A_data = []
    b = []
    w = 1
    d = {} # mapping coordinates with linear indices
    for i in range(n):
        d[(tt[i][0],tt[i][1])] = i
    for i in range(n):
        x = tt[i][0]
        y = tt[i][1]
        if i in k: # if the i-th pixel's depth is known
            A_row.append(equation_num)
            A_col.append(i)
            A_data.append(w)
            b.append(w*depth[x][y])
            equation_num += 1
        else:
            if (x, y-1) in d and (x, y+1) in d:
                if not(i-1 in k and i+1 in k):
                    b.append(2*normal[x][y][0])
                    if i-1 in k:
                        b[-1] += depth[x][y-1]
                    else:
                        A_row.append(equation_num)
                        A_col.append(i-1)
                        A_data.append(-1)
                    if i+1 in k:
                        b[-1] -= depth[x][y+1]
                    else:
                        A_row.append(equation_num)
                        A_col.append(i+1)
                        A_data.append(1)
                    equation_num += 1
                        
            if (x-1, y) in d and (x+1, y) in d:
                if not(d[(x-1, y)] in k and d[(x+1,y)] in k):
                    b.append(2*normal[x][y][1])
                    if d[(x-1, y)] in k:
                        b[-1] += depth[x-1][y]
                    else:
                        A_row.append(equation_num)
                        A_col.append(d[(x-1, y)])
                        A_data.append(-1)
                    if d[(x+1,y)] in k:
                        b[-1] -= depth[x+1][y]
                    else:
                        A_row.append(equation_num)
                        A_col.append(d[(x+1, y)])
                        A_data.append(1)
                    equation_num += 1
    A_row = np.array(A_row)
    A_col = np.array(A_col)
    A_data = np.array(A_data)
    b = np.array(b)
    A = sparse.csr_matrix((A_data, (A_row, A_col)), shape=(equation_num, n))
    res = lsmr(A, b)[0]
    for i in range(n):
        x = tt[i][0]
        y = tt[i][1]
#         if i in k: # if the i-th pixel's depth is known
#             pass
#         else:
        if (x-1, y) in d and (x+1, y) in d and (x, y-1) in d and (x, y+1) in d:
            depth[x][y] = res[i]
    output_depth.append(depth)
    depth = gt_depth.copy()
